}{\plain \fs24 \f1 Several things are worth remarking.  This simile is mainly unadulterated vernacular pastoral with a \softline
few Latinate words (and perhaps a phrase from Virgil at line 77 from }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Georgics}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IV.10, according \softline
to Daniello [comm. to vv. 76-81] and many of those who followed him).  But why does Dante not \softline
get his singulars and plurals straight in the first two elements, only to correct them in the third?  \softline
Why does he include the second element at all, since he excludes it from his summarizing and \softline
concluding third element?  And why, as Torraca (comm. to vv. 76-78) wondered, is the shepherd \softline
standing up (if leaning on his stick) while Virgil and Statius are lying down?  Is that why, Torraca \softline
continued to wonder, Dante included the second element, in which the herdsman is at least closer \softline
to lying down?  The purpose of these questions is to focus attention on how much Dante expects \softline
of his reader.  These little touches, reminding us of his artistic freedom, make us aware of that.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 77.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The phrase }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 rapide e proterve}{\plain \fs24 \f1  in verse 77 (which we have translated as 'quick and \softline
reckless'), according to some commentators, beginning with Benvenuto (comm. to vv. 76-87), \softline
means 'rapaces et temerariae' (rapacious and bold).  Others have objected to the first of these \softline
terms, more fitting to the description of the appetite of a wolf, as being inapplicable to goats.  On \softline
the other hand, if we understood the word to mean 'voracious,' there would be no such problem.  \softline
We, however, believe that Dante is referring to the way a free-roaming goat moves, rather than to \softline
the way it eats, but have no quarrel with those who follow Benvenuto.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 89-90.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The stars look bigger and brighter because Dante is higher up and closer to them \softline
than he has ever been in his life.  There may be a moral atmosphere at work here as well, in that \softline
he has lost the obscuring mantle of sin that is our normal lot (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXX.3), and that also \softline
would make them seem brighter.  For exactly such a twofold understanding see John of Serravalle \softline
(comm. to vv. 88-90).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 94-99.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   It is now before dawn on Wednesday morning, the last day on the mountain, from \softline
which Dante will depart at noon.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab 'Cytherea' is a proper noun formed from the epithet used of the 'maritime' Venus, the \softline
lustful goddess born of the spume of the sea near the island Cythera.  Dante here presents her as \softline
morning star, as she was seen at the opening of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   However, and as has been pointed \softline
out in recent years with increasing insistence, in 1300 Venus was the evening star at this period of \softline
the year, and the morning star only in 1301.  See the discussion in Graziella Federici Vescovini \softline
("Dante e l'astronomia del suo tempo," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Letteratura italiana antica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  3 [2002]), pp. 292, 300n., who \softline
resists the temptation to 'redate' the poem to 1301, believing that Dante is merely taking \softline
advantage of poetic license.  And see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.19-21.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For the formulaic nature of Dante's preparation of his three dream narratives in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
see Hollander (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Allegory in Dante's "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1969]), \softline
p. 149.  All the dreams are preceded by 'an astronomical reference to the hour of the morning at \softline
which the dream occurs' and then by the distinct vocabulary of dream vision, as in the second of 
these tercets: 'in sogno mi parea / donna vedere' (in a dream I seemed to see a lady).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 100-108.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The dream of Leah and Rachel is the most transparent of the three dreams in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IX.13-33 and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XIX.1-33).  Leah and Rachel, the daughters of Laban \softline
in Genesis, were understood by Christian interpreters to represent, respectively, the active life and \softline
the contemplative life (and thus Rachel's staring into the mirror is not to be taken as narcissistic \softline
self-admiration but contemplation in a positive sense).  It is clear that Dante is making use of that \softline
tradition here.  However, he is also making use of biblical typology in his treatment of Leah, who \softline
is related to Eve in her as yet unfallen condition in that she is doing what Adam and Eve were told \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 to do, 'ut }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 operaretur}{\plain \fs24 \f1  et custodiret illum' (to dress [the garden] and keep it -- Genesis 2:15).  \softline
Dante's verb in the last line of Leah's speech, which concludes the dream, remembers the biblical \softline
verb in his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 ovrare}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , the working in this garden that points back to the tasks of that one before the \softline
Fall (see Hollander, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Allegory in Dante's "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: Princeton University Press, \softline
1969], p. 153).  For the balanced relationships between the pair Leah and Rachel and a second \softline
pair, Matelda and Beatrice, the two central female presences in the earthly paradise, see Paola \softline
Pacchioni ("Lia e Rachele, Matelda e Beatrice," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 L'Alighieri}{\plain \fs24 \f1  18 [2001], pp. 47-74).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab It is probably also fair to say that the text intrinsically presents Dante as a new Jacob: 'As \softline
Jacob toiled for seven years in order to gain the hand of Rachel, only to be given that of Leah \softline
(Genesis 29:10f.), so Dante has toiled up seven terraces of purgation with the promise of \softline
Beatrice, only to find Matelda' (Hollander, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Allegory in Dante's "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: \softline
Princeton University Press, 1969], pp. 151-52).  Giovanni Pascoli (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 La mirabile visione}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Bologna: \softline
Zanichelli, 1923 (1902)]), p. 462, had much earlier suggested that Dante, 'the new Aeneas,' was \softline
also the 'new Jacob.'  Pascoli was followed, without their apparent knowledge, by Singleton \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Journey to Beatrice}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Cambridge: Harvard University Press, 1967 (1958)]), p. 108, and by T. K. \softline
Swing (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 The Fragile Leaves of the Sibyl}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Westminster: The Newman Press, 1962]), p. 95.  The \softline
Italian tradition has for a long time insisted only on the 'allegorical' equation here, Leah as the \softline
active life, Rachel as the contemplative.  A figural understanding (i.e., one developed from \softline
'historical allegory,' as in the interpretation of the Bible itself), has mainly been absent.  But see \softline
Momigliano (comm. to these verses) who almost resolves the problem in this way.  Bosco/Reggio \softline
(comm. to vv. 91-108) offer a long and confessedly 'perplexed' attempt to account for the \softline
resulting supposedly double (and thus inadmissible) valence of Beatrice as both 'theology' and 'the \softline
contemplative life.'  For another reading of this dream see Zygmunt Baranski ("Dante's Three \softline
Reflective Dreams," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Quaderni d'italianistica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  10 [1989]), pp. 219-24.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 110-111.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Awakening, the protagonist (and Statius, but Virgil only problematically so) is \softline
associated with travelers who are getting nearer home.  It is quite clear that 'home' now is at the \softline
very least the garden of Eden, and perhaps the true paradise that lies above.  There are no \softline
thoughts of Florence here.  In these lines the true pilgrimage becomes a journey from God, into \softline
the world, and back to God.  It is interesting to compare the beautiful and sad opening of the \softline
eighth canto of this }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , with its traveler whose thoughts are on friends left behind in the \softline
world.  This pilgrim/traveler has apparently learned a good deal on the mountain.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 112.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   For the resonance of a phrase found in the Song of Songs in this verse, 'le tenebre \softline
fuggian da tutti lati' (the shadows all around were being put to flight): 'Donec aspiret dies et \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 inclinentur umbrae' }{\plain \fs24 \f1 (Until the day break and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 the shadows flee away)}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (Cant. 2:17 and 4:6), see 
Eleanor Cook ("Scripture as Enigma: Biblical Allusion in Dante's Earthly Paradise," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante \softline
Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  117 [1999]), p. 5.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 122-123.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This is as close as the poet comes to telling us that the protagonist's last P has \softline
been removed.  He feels as light as his 'feathers.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 125.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Since the garden of Eden seems to be just slightly below the level to which the \softline
travelers have now climbed (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXVIII.4), this topmost step of the stair is the highest \softline
point on earth attained by Dante, and by Virgil as well, but he has no further rising to do.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 127-142.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's final speech in the poem may be clarified by a summarizing paraphrase.  \softline
(1) I have brought you, with intellect and skill, through flames temporal (purgatory) and eternal \softline
(hell) and have reached the limit of my powers; (2) from now on follow your own inclination as \softline
your guide, since you are free; (3) see the sun and the freely growing vegetation here; until \softline
Beatrice, whose weeping eyes sent me to you, comes glad-eyed into your presence, you may \softline
choose to sit or wander; (4) no more do I speak or gesture; your will is free, upright, and whole; \softline
do its pleasure -- and thus do I crown and miter you over yourself.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 127.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Beginning with Scartazzini (comm. to this verse), commentators have cited St. \softline
Thomas to the effect that the pains of the damned are eternal while the fire of purgatory is \softline
temporary.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 131.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   If Dante's will is as good as Virgil will shortly say it is, he can take pleasure as his \softline
guide because he will only want that which reason will want.  Nothing sinful would any longer \softline
tempt him.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
