400-1, to allegorize the crown and miter that Virgil awards Dante as (1) the triumphant laurel of \softline
the modern poet and (2) the Christian truth that he can add to Virgil's store of pagan wisdom and \softline
poetic technique.  As Remo Fasani ("Canto XXVII," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis Turicensis: Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , \softline
ed. Georges G{\f2\u252\'fc}ntert and Michelangelo Picone [Florence: Cesati, 2001]), p. 432, points out, \softline
although the modern discussion has tended to treat the terms as synonyms, as long ago as in the \softline
commentaries of the Ottimo (comm. to vv. 139-142) and of Francesco da Buti (comm. to vv. \softline
124-142), they were understood as separate entities.  To the Ottimo they signified 'rector and \softline
shepherd'; to Francesco, laurel crown ('}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 corono}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ; di laurea, come poeta') and bishop's miter ('come \softline
vescovo e guidatore dell'anima tua a l'eterna salute' [as bishop and guide over your own soul, \softline
bound for eternal salvation]), two very different sorts of adornment for Dante's head.  Fasani opts \softline
for the crown as sign of Dante's active life, his temporal (and decidedly imperial) political mission, \softline
and sees the miter as an image of his contemplative life, the poet's spiritual mission.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab In the recent and continuing argument there are those who argue, as did Contini (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Un' idea \softline
